2) trace.csv: Group by cmdb_id and trace_name for the same component list. For each group compute: count (full series), p50, p95, mean, std of value (full series) and count_in_window in the same timestamp range. Return [cmdb_id, trace_name, count, p50, p95, mean, std, count_in_window], sorted by count_in_window then count, limit top 50 rows.

3) log.csv: Group by cmdb_id and log_name for the same component list. For each group compute: count (full series), p50, p95, mean, std of value (full series) and count_in_window in the same timestamp range. Return [cmdb_id, log_name, count, p50, p95, mean, std, count_in_window], sorted by count_in_window then count, limit top 50 rows.

4) error_logs.csv: Return total row count, and number of rows with timestamp in the incident window, and show up to first 5 rows within the window (if any).

Notes: 
- Do NOT calculate thresholds using only incident-window data; compute p95/p50 over the entire available series for each group first.
- Keep all returned tables compact (<=50 rows each). Save full intermediate DataFrames in kernel variables but do not print them.
- Use UTC+8 timezone treatment for interpreting timestamps (Executor will handle timestamp->datetime conversion where needed).
